org.cleartk.classifier
Interface Classifier<OUTCOME_TYPE>

All Known Implementing Classes:
BinaryLIBSVMClassifier, Classifier_ImplBase, LIBLINEARClassifier, LIBSVMClassifier, MalletClassifier, MalletCRFClassifier, MaxentClassifier, MultiClassLIBSVMClassifier, OVASVMlightClassifier, SVMlightClassifier
public interface Classifier<OUTCOME_TYPE>


Copyright (c) 2007-2008, Regents of the University of Colorado
All rights reserved.

This class provides an abstraction for interfacing with various ML learning libraries such as Mallet, Libsvm, OpenNLP Maxent, etc. Each subclass must override the abstract methods (naturally!) each of which is documented below. Each subclass must also be able to be instantiated from a single jar file that contains all the necessary meta-data and data (e.g. the model). The contents of the jar file will vary for each implementation. However, each jar file should have a manifest file with two attributes, "returnType" and "classifier". The jar command can be used to set the manifest of a jar file. A manifest file should look something like this: 

  Manifest-Version: 1.0
  classifier: org.cleartk.classifier.OpenNLPMaxentClassifier
  returnType: string

Author:
Philipp Wetzler, Philip Ogren

classifySequence

List<OUTCOME_TYPE> classifySequence(List<List<Feature>> features)
This method provides a default implementation for classifying a bunch of instances at once. The values returned are the same as they would if classify(List<Feature>) was called individually on each list of features. Sequential classifiers should override this method.

Parameters:
features - a list of lists of features.
Returns:
a list of values corresponding to the classifications made.
See Also:
MalletCRFClassifier.classify(List)

score

ScoredValue<OUTCOME_TYPE> score(List<Feature> features)
Provides a way to get a score associated with a classification. The 'score' in the scored value could be anything but is often a probability. The only expectation is that a higher score should correspond to higher confidence in the classification. No other assumptions should be made.

Parameters:
features - a list of features to be classified
Returns:
the classification score

score

List<ScoredValue<OUTCOME_TYPE>> score(List<Feature> features,
                                      int maxResults)
Provides a way to get a scores associated with the top N scores for the best N classifications. The 'score' in the scored value could be anything but is often a probability. The only expectation is that a higher score should correspond to higher confidence in the classification. No other assumptions should be made.

Parameters:
features - a list of features to be classified
maxResults - the maximum number of classifications to return.
Returns:
a sorted list of the best N classifications with their scores.

isSequential

boolean isSequential()
A classifier that is based on a sequence of labels (i.e. computes/optimizes label transition probabilities) such as the MalletCRFClassifier should return true. Here is the expectation for implementors. If true is returned, then the classifier may or may not implement classify(List<Feature>) (usually not we expect) and must override classify(List<List<Feature>>). If false is returned, then the classifier is required to implement classify(List<Feature>) and may or many not override classify(List<List<Feature>>). If you do not want to implement classify(List<Feature>) for your sequential classifier, then simply throw an UnsupportedOperationException.

Returns:
true if this is a sequential classifier, false otherwise.
See Also:
MalletCRFClassifier.isSequential(), MaxentClassifier.isSequential()
